HttpClient contains a number of methods to send an HttpClientRequest to an Http server and receive an HttpClientResponse back. For example, you can use the get, getUrl, post, and postUrl methods for GET and POST requests, respectively.
HttpRequest and HttpClientResponse always have immutable headers.
HttpRequest can be used to obtain data from HTTP and FTP protocols, and is useful for AJAX-style page updates.
HttpResponse and HttpClientRequest have immutable headers from the moment the body is written to.

I/O operations can block a program for some period of time while it waits for the operation to complete. To avoid this, all methods involving I/O have an asynchronous variant which returns a Future. This future completes when the I/O operation finishes. While the I/O operation is in progress, the Dart program is not blocked, and can perform other operations.
